{
  "text": "Given the complex effects of IL1a signalling in the mutant mouse, it became imperative to determine how the loss of caspase 8 regulates the secretion (and therefore the activity) of this cytokine. Two proteases have been implicated in the conversion of the interleukin 1 precursor into its active form: caspase 1 and calpain [CITATION_1] . In both the caspase 8 null epidermis and wounded skin there is an upregulation of caspase 1 RNA and suprabasal localization of the protein (Fig. 4a,  b) . Furthermore, the amount of IL1a secreted from epidermal sheets is 2.5-fold higher in the knockout mouse than its wild-type littermate and this increase is lost when treated with a caspase 1 (but not the calpain) inhibitor (Fig. 4c) . These results are supported by reports that the overexpression of caspase 1 (ref. [CITATION_2] or IL1a (ref. [CITATION_3] in the epidermis phenocopies the caspase 8 conditional knockout.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "40902023",
